04552nam a22006735i 9780691188522DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911885227 a10.1515/97806911885222doi  a(DE-B1597)501913  a(OCoLC)1076411610  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJX1391b.R585 1990eb 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a327.12231 aRosenau, James N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTurbulence in World Politics :bA Theory of Change and Continuity /cJames N. Rosenau. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES -- tTABLES -- tPREFACE -- tPART ONE: ORGANIZED OVERVIEW -- tPART TWO: ESSENTIAL ELEMENTS -- tPART THREE: PROBING PARAMETERS -- tPART FOUR: TURBULENT TRANSFORMATIONS -- tPART FIVE: SEEKING SOLUTIONS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this ambitious work a leading scholar undertakes a full-scale reconceptualization of international relations. Turbulence in World Politics is an entirely new formulation that accounts for the persistent turmoil of today's world, even as it also probes the impact of the microelectronic revolution, the postindustrial order, and the many other fundamental political, economic, and social changes under way since World War II. To develop this formulation, James N. Rosenau digs deep into the workings of communities and the orientations of individuals that culminate in collective action on the world stage. His concern is less with questions of epistemology and methodology and more with the development of a comprehensive theoryone that is different from other paradigms in the field by virtue of its focus on the tumult in contemporary international relations. The book depicts a bifurcation of global politics in which an autonomous multi-centric world has emerged as a competitor of the long established state-centric world. A central theme is that the analytic skills of people everywhere are expanding and thereby altering the context in which international processes unfold. Rosenau shows how the macro structures of global politics have undergone transformations linked to those at the micro level: long-standing structures of authority weaken, collectivities fragment, subgroups become more powerful at the expense of states and governments, national loyalties are redirected, and new issues crowd onto the global agenda. These turbulent dynamics foster the simultaneous centralizing and decentralizing tendencies that are now bifurcating global structures. "Rosenau's new work is an imaginative leap into world politics in the twenty-first century. There is much here to challenge traditional thought of every persuasion." --Michael Brecher, McGill University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInternational relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188522zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691188522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188522.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK